+# Contribution–Access Network (CAN)
+## WP-006: Operationalising Graph Settlement — Simulation, Governance Stress Testing, and Deployment Framework
+
+**Working Paper WP-006**  
+**Status:** Technical & Deployment Specification  
+**Version:** 1.0  
+**Date:** 2026  
+
+---
+
+## Abstract
+
+WP-005 formalised the Six-Degree Network Ledger Architecture and Non-Monetary Complex Settlement (NMCS) as the structural evolution of CAN.
+
+WP-006 operationalises that architecture by specifying:
+
+- Computational implementation of graph settlement
+- Weight decay and trust propagation models
+- Simulation framework for multi-hop coordination
+- Adversarial stress testing mechanisms
+- Governance cell deployment model
+- Phased real-world rollout strategy
+
+Where WP-005 established theory and structure, WP-006 establishes execution.
+
+---
+
+## 1. Objective
+
+To demonstrate that:
+
+1. Graph settlement is computationally feasible at scale
+2. Trust propagation can be stabilised across large networks
+3. NMCS remains robust under adversarial conditions
+4. Hybrid transition can occur without institutional shock
+
+---
+
+## 2. Computational Model
+
+### 2.1 Graph Definition
+
+Let:
+
+**G(t) = (N, E, W(t))**
+
+Where:
+
+- N = participants
+- E = verified enablement edges
+- W(t) = time-dependent weight matrix
+
+Each edge e(i, j) may carry:
+
+- contribution weight (c)
+- reliability modifier (r)
+- validation multiplier (v)
+- decay factor over degree distance (d^k)
+
+Total propagated contribution is computed without tokens and without transferability.
+
+### 2.2 Degree Decay
+
+Impact decays over network distance to prevent permanent dominance and infinite accumulation.
+
+Example options:
+
+- exponential: d^k = e^(−λk)
+- linear capped: d^k = max(0, 1 − αk)
+- adaptive: adjust decay using path redundancy
+
+---
+
+## 3. Trust Computation
+
+Trust(A → Z) is computed as an aggregate of validated paths weighted by:
+
+- path length (degree distance)
+- reliability persistence
+- governance validation
+- redundancy (multi-path confirmation)
+
+Clique/collusion risks are mitigated via:
+
+- path diversity requirements
+- reinforcement caps
+- anomaly detection
+- random audits
+
+---
+
+## 4. Access Allocation Engine
+
+Access priority is computed per resource pool as a vector:
+
+P(n, pool) = w1(C_direct) + w2(C_propagated) + w3(Trust) + w4(Reliability) + w5(Need) − w6(Overconcentration)
+
+Weights are pool-specific and governance-controlled.
+
+---
+
+## 5. Simulation Framework
+
+### 5.1 Baseline Network Simulation
+
+Test:
+
+- 10^3–10^6 nodes
+- varying participation rates
+- varying validation strictness
+- adversarial injection rates
+
+Measure:
+
+- allocation variance and fairness
+- concentration drift
+- trust collapse thresholds
+- recovery time after shocks
+
+### 5.2 Platform Topology Simulation (Creator → User → Advertiser → Platform)
+
+Model:
+
+- A → Z (free informational provision)
+- Z → Y (attention)
+- Y → B (revenue)
+
+Replace central redistribution logic with NMCS propagation.
+
+Measure:
+
+- creator stability
+- dependency reduction on central payout
+- resilience under demand shocks
+
+### 5.3 Free-Rider Stress Test
+
+Inject passive actors and observe:
+
+- trust decay
+- tier pressure (access reduction without punitive deprivation)
+- system stability under 5/10/20% passive rates
+
+---
+
+## 6. Governance Cell Deployment
+
+Cells manage:
+
+- local validation
+- edge verification
+- appeals and disputes
+- parameter tuning per pool
+
+Safeguards:
+
+- rotation and term limits
+- cross-cell arbitration
+- transparent audit trails
+
+---
+
+## 7. Hybrid Deployment Strategy
+
+Phased rollout:
+
+1. institutional pilots (bounded domains)
+2. multi-pool integration (cross-domain graph)
+3. monetary shrinkage (price mediation reduces where graph settlement performs)
+
+Money remains a compliance interface where required.
+
+---
+
+## 8. Adversarial Models
+
+Stress tests include:
+
+- trust ring inflation
+- contribution spam
+- governance capture attempts
+
+Mitigation relies on:
+
+- diversity requirements
+- auditability
+- anomaly detection
+- contestability and arbitration
+
+---
+
+## 9. Outcomes and Metrics
+
+Define measurable indicators:
+
+- concentration coefficient
+- trust dispersion index
+- allocation fairness variance
+- retention rate of contributors
+- shock recovery time
+
+These metrics serve as empirical validation criteria for CAN deployments.
+
+---
+
+## 10. Conclusion
+
+WP-005 defined the architecture.
+
+WP-006 defines operationalisation.
+
+Graph settlement is simulation-ready, governance-testable, and deployable in hybrid environments without requiring abrupt abolition of monetary systems.
